  "prompt": "What is the difference between collateral and mortgage?",
  "response": "Collateral and mortgage are terms commonly used in finance and real estate, but they refer to different concepts:\n\n1. **Collateral**:\n   - Collateral is an asset or property that a borrower offers to a lender to secure a loan. It acts as a guarantee that the lender can recover some or all of the loan amount if the borrower defaults on the repayment.\n   - Collateral can take various forms, including real estate, vehicles, stocks, bonds, or other valuable items. The specific asset used as collateral can depend on the type of loan and the lender's requirements.\n\n2. **Mortgage**:\n   - A mortgage is a specific type of loan used to purchase real estate, where the property itself serves as collateral for the loan. When a borrower takes out a mortgage, they agree to pay back the loan amount, plus interest, over a predetermined period.\n   - The mortgage is a legal agreement that gives the lender the right to take ownership of the property (through foreclosure) if the borrower fails to make the required payments.\n\nIn summary, all mortgages involve collateral (the property being financed), but not all collateral is a mortgage. Collateral can be any asset used to secure a loan, while a mortgage specifically refers to a loan secured by real estate.",
